---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import QBIDeductionCalculator from "../../components/QBIDeductionCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="QBI Deduction Calculator | Section 199A Pass-Through Tax Savings"
  description="Calculate your Section 199A Qualified Business Income deduction. See exactly how the 20% deduction, W-2 wage limits, and SSTB rules affect your tax savings."
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@graph": [
      {
        "@type": "FinanceApplication",
        "name": "QBI Deduction Calculator",
        "applicationCategory": "FinanceApplication",
        "operatingSystem": "Web",
        "provider": {
          "@id": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/#organization"
        },
        "offers": {
          "@type": "Offer",
          "price": "0",
          "priceCurrency": "USD"
        },
        "description": "Calculate your Section 199A Qualified Business Income deduction. See exactly how the 20% deduction, W-2 wage limits, and SSTB rules affect your tax savings."
      },
      {
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What counts as a Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB)?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "SSTBs include law, health, consulting, financial and investment services, accounting, performing arts, and similar fields where the business's principal asset is the reputation or skill of its owners or employees. SSTB owners lose the QBI deduction entirely once taxable income rises above the phase-in range for their filing status."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Is the QBI deduction still available in 2026?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Yes. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act, signed in July 2025, made the Section 199A QBI deduction permanent. Starting in 2026, businesses with at least $1,000 of qualified business income can also claim a new $400 minimum deduction, even if the standard calculation would produce less."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "How does my S-Corp salary affect my QBI deduction?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Once your income is inside the phase-in range, your QBI deduction can be limited by W-2 wages paid by the business. For S-Corp owners, a higher reasonable salary increases W-2 wages (which can raise the wage-based limitation) but also reduces the pass-through profit that QBI is calculated on — so the two amounts need to be modeled together, not in isolation."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
        "itemListElement": [
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 1,
            "name": "Home",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/"
          },
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 2,
            "name": "QBI Deduction Calculator",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/qbi-deduction-calculator/"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

  <main class="flex-grow max-w-7xl w-full mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-6 sm:py-10">

    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        QBI Deduction Calculator (Section 199A)
      </h1>
      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-xs font-medium text-slate-500 bg-slate-900/50 inline-flex px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg border border-slate-800">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-4 w-4 text-[#00F5D4]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m5.618-4.016A11.955 11.955 0 0112 2.944a11.955 11.955 0 01-8.618 3.04A12.02 12.02 0 003 9c0 5.591 3.824 10.29 9 11.622 5.176-1.332 9-6.03 9-11.622 0-1.042-.133-2.052-.382-3.016z"/></svg>
          <span>Reviewed by <a href="/editorial-policy/" class="text-slate-400 hover:text-[#00F5D4] transition-colors underline decoration-slate-700 underline-offset-2">Editorial Staff</a></span>
        </div>
        <span class="hidden sm:inline text-slate-700">&bull;</span>
        <time datetime="2026-07-21" class="text-slate-400">Updated: July 2026</time>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Calculate your Section 199A Qualified Business Income deduction, including the W-2 wage/UBIA limitation and SSTB phase-out rules, now permanent under the One Big Beautiful Bill Act.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component Island -->
    <QBIDeductionCalculator />

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16">
        <section>
          <div class="mb-6">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20 mb-4">Financial Tool</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Understand Your Pass-Through Business Deduction
            </h2>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-8 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Introduction</h3>
              <p>The Section 199A Qualified Business Income (QBI) deduction lets owners of sole proprietorships, S-Corps, partnerships, and other pass-through entities deduct up to 20% of their qualified business income. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (OBBBA), signed in July 2025, made this deduction permanent — but the W-2 wage/UBIA limitation and SSTB rules still meaningfully reduce it for higher earners. Use this calculator to see your actual deduction, not just the headline 20%.</p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Key Benefits</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
                <li>See your instant deduction estimate and resulting tax savings.</li>
                <li>Understand whether you're below, inside, or above the phase-in range.</li>
                <li>See exactly how SSTB status affects your deduction as income rises.</li>
                <li>Model how adjusting W-2 wages (e.g. via your S-Corp reasonable salary) changes your result.</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20 mb-4">FAQ</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>

            <div class="space-y-4">

              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">What counts as a Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB)?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  SSTBs include law, health, consulting, financial and investment services, accounting, performing arts, and similar fields where the business's principal asset is the reputation or skill of its owners or employees. SSTB owners lose the QBI deduction entirely once taxable income rises above the phase-in range for their filing status.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">Is the QBI deduction still available in 2026?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  Yes. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act, signed in July 2025, made the Section 199A QBI deduction permanent. Starting in 2026, businesses with at least $1,000 of qualified business income can also claim a new $400 minimum deduction, even if the standard calculation would produce less.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">How does my S-Corp salary affect my QBI deduction?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  Once your income is inside the phase-in range, your QBI deduction can be limited by W-2 wages paid by the business. For S-Corp owners, a higher reasonable salary increases W-2 wages (which can raise the wage-based limitation) but also reduces the pass-through profit that QBI is calculated on — so the two amounts need to be modeled together, not in isolation.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Internal Links -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Related Calculators &amp; Resources</h3>
            <div class="flex flex-col space-y-2">
              <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">S-Corp Tax Calculator</a>
              <a href="/salt-cap-deduction-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">SALT Cap Deduction Calculator</a>
              <a href="/debt-payoff-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Debt Payoff Calculator</a>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Methodology & Sources -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-500/20 mb-4">Methodology</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">How This is Calculated</h3>
            <div class="text-sm text-slate-400 space-y-3 leading-relaxed">
              <p>This calculator estimates the tentative QBI deduction as 20% of qualified business income, capped by 20% of taxable income before the deduction. Below the phase-in threshold for your filing status, no further limitation applies. Inside the phase-in range, the deduction blends linearly toward the W-2 wage/UBIA limitation (the greater of 50% of W-2 wages, or 25% of W-2 wages plus 2.5% of UBIA). Above the phase-in range, the wage/UBIA limitation applies in full, and SSTBs lose the deduction entirely. A $400 minimum deduction applies for active businesses with at least $1,000 of QBI, per the One Big Beautiful Bill Act effective 2026.</p>
              <p>This is a simplified model for estimation purposes — it does not account for net capital gains adjustments, aggregation elections, or multiple pass-through entities. Consult a tax professional for your specific situation.</p>
              <p><strong>Official Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">IRS.gov — Qualified Business Income Deduction</a></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
